  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 18:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Paul immediately ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "gave practical proof",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of this solemn renunciation of the Jews by departing from the synagogue (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐκεῖθεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which Heinrichs and Alford after Calvin explain, contrary to the context, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ex domo Aguilae",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and went, not into the house of a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jew",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but into that of a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "proselyte",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the otherwise unknown ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Justus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", who is not to be identified with Titus (Wieseler). That Paul betook himself to the non-Jewish house ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "nearest",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to the synagogue, is entirely in keeping with the profoundly excited emotion under which he acted, and with his decision of character.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "συνομορεῖν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to border upon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is not found elsewhere; the Greeks use ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁμορεῖν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in that sense. Observe, moreover, that a change of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "lodging",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is not mentioned.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 18:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μεταβὰς ἐκεῖθεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from the synagogue, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 10:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “he removed,” Rendall; “he changed his place ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "from the synagogue",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",” Ramsay: the verb is found three times with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐκεῖθεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in St. Matthew, and in each place “departed” R.V., this gives perfectly good sense: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Ramsay, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Church in the Roman Empire",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 158, and critical note.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἰούστου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": if the addition ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Τίτου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Τιτίου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is correct, there is no need to discuss the possible identification with the companion of St. Paul in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Galatians 2:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; see Alford and Page, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in loco",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and critical note. The identification was adopted by Chrysostom and Grotius, and for a statement of the evidence on either side see Plumptre, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in loco",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It should be remembered that we have Barsabbas Justus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 1:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and Jesus Justus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Colossians 4:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see also Lightfoot “Acts of the Apostles,” B.D.2, i., 32. The house of a proselyte may have been chosen because it offered easy access to those who wished to come, whether Greeks or Hebrews (see Chrysostom’s comment), but in Paul’s thus going into the house of a proselyte hard by the synagogue we may see how his spirit had been stirred. But further: this Titus Justus was evidently a Roman citizen, one of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "coloni",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in Corinth, and thus St. Paul would gain access through him to the more educated class in the city, Ramsay, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "St. Paul",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 256, and “Corinth,” Hastings’ B.D., i. 480.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "συνομοροῦσα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": there is no need to suppose that he left his lodgings with Aquila—this house became Paul’s place of meeting (so in Ephesus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 19:9-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); he had his own synagogue there (Blass); in classics simple verb ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁμορέω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁμουρέω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; compound only found here; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "συνόμορος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Eccl[319] writers.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[319]ccl. ecclesiastical.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a certain man’s house, named Justus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] He used this house for the purposes of teaching and worship. We may suppose that for his own lodging, he still remained with Aquila and Priscilla. Some MSS. give the name Titus Justus to this man, and the double name is adopted in the Revised Version, but there is good authority for the received text.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "one that worshipped God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] He was a Proselyte. The word is used of religious proselytes (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 13:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and of devout Greeks (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 17:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). His house was therefore an appropriate place in which both Jews and Gentiles might meet, and to which Gentiles would be more ready to come than to that of a Jew by birth.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "whose house joined hard to the synagogue",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] It is likely that St Paul, though he came no more to the synagogue at Corinth, chose not to betake himself far away, because he would be ready to receive any of his brethren who might change their feelings and come to him. But we can see how, while his near neighbourhood gave opportunity for this, the meetings of those who came to the synagogue with those who were going to the house of Justus, would be likely to cause bitterness, especially when the number of St Paul’s adherents began to increase, and a ruler of the synagogue was counted among them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 18:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἐκεῖθεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "thence",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") So also ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 19:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—V. g.]—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἰούστου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "of Justus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") a Gentile.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "συνομοροῦσα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "adjoining to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") So that those who frequented the synagogue might further [besides] hear the doctrine concerning Jesus Christ.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 7.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "- Went",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "entered",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the house of a certain man",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a certain man's house",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Titus Justus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Justus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V. and T.R. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thence",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Clearly from the synagogue, where he had been preaching to the Jews, not from Aquila's house, as Alford and others. It does not appear to be a question here of where Paul lodged, but where he preached. Justus had probably a large room, which he gave Paul the use of for his sabbath and other meetings. As Howson truly says, he continued to \"lodge\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "μένειν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") with Aquila and Priscilla. It is only said that he \"came\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ῆλθεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to the house of Justus from the synagogue. So Renan, \"Il ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "enseigna",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " desor-mais dans la maison de Titius Justus\" (p. 216). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "One that worshipped God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "σεβομένον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τὸν Θεόν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " a Greek proselyte of the gate (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 13:43, 50",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 16:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 17:4, 17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.) Cornelius is called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "εὐσεβὴς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "καὶ φοβούμενος τὸν Θεόν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Whose house",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. Either his proximity to the synagogue had led to his attending there, or, being already a proselyte, he had taken a house hard by for the convenience of attending. Joined hard; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ῆν συνομοροῦσα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", found only here either in the New Testament or elsewhere. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Ὁμορέω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " occurs in Plutarch; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "συνόμορος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is also a word (Steph., 'Thesaur.'). Acts 18:7",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]